So - back your local - indeed national - TTI. Wear masks. Use the App. Be sensible over Christmas, in particular for at risk people (basically over 60).

We frankly wont know until it is tried, and we will need to be able to move things up in NPIs to balance any lack of efficacy of TTI. But... these things *can* work and they *can* improve and I know alot of people work super hard to do so every day of the week.

There is every reason to think it can work better; furthermore many aspects of Trace work better if prevelance is lower. Both these bode well for post lockdown that (new) Tier 3 should reduce transmission and (new) Tier 2 can hold or slowly reduce transmission

Mainly as envisaged in early September it could not hold in most contexts in the UK; however, it was close in the East of England, and in "old" Tier 3 (Liverpool) for NPIs the combination then clearly worked.
(context being - winter or not, other NPIs or not, population density, occupation spread of people and other things specific to each grouping of people).

So - back to my moan - has it "failed"? This goes straight to the definition of success - pick your definition and it will get over those bars or not. One natural definition is whether it can hold transmission down, and then one has to define the context
We've got to stay focused here on what works; both instincts about how to deliver this, experience worldwide and recent changes suggest this works best locally again.

The "I" is isolation. Testing and Tracing is pointless without effective isolation support. This one I have less of a line of sight on personally but it needs careful attention. Isolation support is a multipler on the others.
This is all about people and details and so the least easy to write snappy stories about or to see obvious phase changes in delivery.

Lots of details to this, lots of people working hard now in systems that don't align to the task at hand. I am a cheerleader and enthusiast for bringing in successful Trace schemes (Japan being one) and getting them to work in the UK context.
One positive is the high number of people with the App in the UK, which is good, and QR codes for locations which I hope post lockdown can be used more.

The next T, "Trace", is the cinderella at the ball. This is all about people, best done locally, and the UK systems are clunky to unworkable. Here the push to more happening locally is good, and we are allowed to learn more from successful Trace operations.

So - on the first "T" - test, the UK tests now deeply and the response rate for tests is pretty good (>50% in under 48 hours). Yes, it could be better but you'd take this. Extra bonus marks in the UK with integration into genomic sequencing afterwards (go!)
(Hubris is very likely to get punished in a pandemic; goes with inappropriate optimism).

First off - none of this is perfect (eyes passim to "world beating" etc) - as a number of people have said, one wants to just have things that work. This goes to my coronavirus is like golf - ultimately it is each country "against the course" and not a direct competition.

Finland has an opportunity to become known as the European country that handled COVID-19 better than its peers. It can also squander this opportunity by not taking decisive action. With the vaccines providing an exit from the acute crisis next year, we can‚Äôt give in.

What we propose in this memo is adoption of a clearer national strategy to push the number of cases close to 0, ongoing investment in goal-oriented, streamlined measures including population screenings, and better engagement and incentives for local and regional operators. https://t.co/LGRRKWXjJi

Finland has what it takes to suppress the epidemic, if a clear strategy and corresponding methods are adopted and executed well. The isolated location, structure of the society, and a pretty functional test-trace-isolate operation and other already implemented policies help.

Suppression of the epidemic is not painless, but it is by far the best of the available options. It protects lives, public health, individual freedom, equality and the economy. An epidemic at or close to zero cases/day is also dramatically easier and cheaper to manage.

Now there‚Äôs bad outbreak in the Helsinki area, following a slow growth over many months. This demonstrates the dangers of just managing and not suppressing the epidemic. It‚Äôs time to draw conclusions from experiences worldwide: you should suppress the epidemic if you only can. https://t.co/cxI1MCqJLC

Finland managed pretty well in the spring, avoiding a strict lockdown and ending up with just a few cases/day in the summer. In the fall, the epidemic re-emerged but has been thus far mild compared to rest of Europe, and many local outbreaks have been decisevly extinguished.

I'm delighted to share the English version of our recent memo about why and how Finland must adopt a stronger strategy to suppress the COVID-19 epidemic. This is the third major memo by our independent, multidisciplinary expert group. https://t.co/Ksw9754NMb

I don't always chat about potatoes, but when I do it sure seems to be ranty and late at night.
And why there's so much interest in reforming potatoes into a seed-grown crop.

Clonally produced onions and potatoes is ideal for small-scale production.Seed produced onions and potatoes is ideal for large-scale production. This is why onions were reformed. The potato industry has layers and layers to compensate for the difficulty with clonal potatoes.

They used to be primarily grown from saved bulbs. We call those older style onions, "potato onions" because they're planted like potatoes.Potato onions were largely abandoned, but have recently experienced a revival thanks to breeder Kelly Winterton. https://t.co/4stK1PgNBK
The conversion of a clonally propagated crop into a seed grown crop has happened before.Onions are generally grown from seed, though you may grow them from "starts" that were seeds not long before.

Seeds can be stored longer and cheaper than potatoes. Potato breeding companies will be able to store more genetic lines in their archives for less cost. Farmers will be able to access more varieties to grow and gain higher profits. Customers may also gain better prices.

Overall, our results suggest the direct and indirect mechanisms by which gain-of-function mutant p53 targets the chromatin and subsequent gene expression patterns in a tumour-type specific manner.

By integrating gene expression data, we found that some of the genes linked to the differential accessibility showed significant expression change in matched tumour samples. This includes some of the known and novel genes regulated by mutant p53. https://t.co/OwKVCzjDpZ

Moreover, the gained and lost peaks show significant enrichment of binding motifs for known co-factors of mutant p53 and other master TF regulators, and enhancer marks in a tumour-type specific manner. https://t.co/5FEXvKphKt

The overlap of gained or lost peaks with the previously known mutant p53 binding regions (inferred from ChIP-seq data) is less. This suggests that the mutant p53 could preferentially bind to the existing open chromatin regions. https://t.co/RpWAbOBGgx

In mutant p53 tumours, the number of genomic regions  with loss of chromatin accessibility is relatively higher than the gained peaks, in both cancer types. This can be attributed to the loss of wild-type p53 transcription factor activity. https://t.co/LvZUL8U3sD

In summary: we now have 3 SARS_CoV_2 vaccines which, on summary reports of early data, work. We should be overjoyed. Understanding efficacy and details is important, but will come. Scale up, logistics and roll out is also important; let's get to a better world as soon as possible

As we will likely give the vaccine in a variable way in some roll out (in particular with HCWs getting it early, there will be another broad early group). It is worth noting all the trials are likely to continue for a fair while longer (so each of these estimates will improve)

Clearly we need the papers (all 3 trials in fact) - and clearly it would be cleaner if the variable dosing arm was randomised explicitly but it reminds you that the immune system is ... not something we understand. Welcome to science!

(One might get into "near Oxford" vs "far from Oxford" confounders but remember this is about a shift in efficacy, not a "does it work" and randomisation happened *throughout* - the HF has a matched sham arm).

This randomisation is within the age group (18-55) and within one country (UK) and it is likely that the mirror full-full dose of age group (18-55) and country (UK) will be fine to use the dosing regieme shift as a natural experiment.

Now this is a sub-group analysis (which immediately triggers concerns) but it is not a post-hoc sub-group creation (which is the worst thing to do). It is a "natural experiment" addition to the trial.

Back to the efficacy numbers; the half-dose full-dose trial has seemingly higher efficacy than full-full. Now there is a shift around of subgroups / countries in the full-full but the signal is all coming from the half-dose full-dose improve (4 vaccinated plays 34 sham)

However, one thing will not change no matter what we do. Our individual attention capacity will not increase. We will filter science by some means and whatever replaces the impact factor will have its own problems.

If you are outraged by how much Nature thinks it should costs to publish put all your papers out as preprints, tell all your colleagues to do the same. That is the seed that will allow us to build a different/better publishing system.

Unfortunately, disruptive revolutions in publishing are nearly impossible. We need to increase the evolvability of publishing, foster an environment where alternatives can be tested. This is why preprints are critical, they separate the act of publishing from filtering/credit.

Many have argued that the system of tiered journals selects only for fraud. I disagree, they have some usefulness as a filter https://t.co/joMSyfKHJL but I agree that they are by no means costs efficient. We could do a lot better if it was easier to change practices.

Everyone should clearly realise that we have always payed this cost through subscriptions. Having these costs in the open is important because it is easier to ask if this system is worth it. Is the filtering needed, useful, cost efficient?

aka - can a given indicator at some time t predict something at time t+1. this is why a ton of things look awesome in backtest and fail in forward test.

that said, posterior probability isn't that useful, since ideally your indicator will make money and hold into the future. what you should be most interested in is the usefulness of predicting prior probability [cont.]

I'm not an epidemiologist, nor an economist. I'm repeating things I've heard others say, just in case someone listens and pays attention to my words instead.You can't be too paranoid about COVID-19 infection. Think about what you'll be doing two weeks from now, and do it *NOW*!

Complete lockdown. For at least a month. It needs to be done six months ago, but now is the second-best time. Lock down now, or COVID-19 will do it for you, decimating the population because there'll be no hospitals left to help people live with the disease.

Don't punish people for staying at home. Don't make people feel guilty about staying home.That means letting people live without money. It means freezing anything that could increase the debt people have. It means giving people whatever they need to survive away from others.

Spend that testing money instead on people who need it. Assume that everyone is infected (or every second person, if it makes people act urgently), and behave accordingly. That means staying at home. It means shutting down any work that doesn't keep people living and healthy.

In the US, the probability is essentially 1 that one of the people you have been next to for more than 15 minutes in the last two weeks has COVID-19. In which case you should stay home and isolate away from others, because there's a high risk that the virus has also infected you.

Here's my perspective: It's a waste of money to test when the case rate is as high as it is in the US. What possible benefit could it have? Are people going to be more likely to stay at home if they think they've got COVID-19?I've got a cheaper approach: assume everyone has it.

People in the US: don't wait for a positive test result before you isolate yourself. Stay home *now*.It's not really possible to be too paranoid about COVID-19 infection.I wrote this up on SoylentNews, but figured I might as well tweet this as well....

Two more comments:1. There was (is?) a debate about releasing GWAS sumstats, with similar concerns (https://t.co/r53X1hSTCZ)2. There might be ways to minimize Reidentifiability risk by e.g. introducing small perturbations and/or imposing a minimum MAF threshold @Hoon_Cho8/9

Privacy concern: If we have a person's genome, we can use in-sample LD from a GWAS to probabilistically infer if they're in the GWAS. Not a big deal if the GWAS is e.g. the UK Biobank, but could be a very big deal if it's a disease GWAS. üò¨7/9

Open question:Is it time for GWAS studies to start releasing in-sample LD, similarly to sumstats? It's a technical challenge, but not a deal-breaker in 2020 (~2TB of storage per GWAS cohort).The main concern is privacy risksüëá6/9

Ideal solution:Use in-sample LD (=compute LD in the GWAS data). That's what we did in our paper, using 337K UKB British (the data is available: https://t.co/hXpqQMtJky)But:Usually we don't have in-sample LD, and we can't compute it ourselves unless we have the GWAS data5/9

This problem is really under-appreciated. I would argue that the biggest obstacle to fine-mapping nowadays is that we don't have good LD ref-panels. We're missing *thousands* of disease SNPs because we don't have good LD data. The implications to drug discovery are huge.4/9

Problem:The methods pretend that the sumstats and LD data came from the same dataset, but they didn't. This can be a *big* problem: In fine-mapping we get many false-positives (see Table 2 in our paper). In PRS we lose lots of accuracy. And in general, nasty stuff happens.3/9

Background:Almost all statsgen methods can use sumstats and LD reference panels, instead of individual-level genotypes. This is cool, because we can combine sumstats from a GWAS with LD data from a reference panel like 1000g. But:2/9

And with each tiny glass bulb shattered, the probability that the whole strand will short out entirely grows.So that's 2020 I guess. Sitting and eating sushi alone on my bday because a metaphorical steamroller operator can't be bothered to learn how to stop.

This past year has been like watching a steamroller slowly crushing a string of lights- each cracking bulb tiny, but the frustration grows as you try to get the driver to stop and they just...won't, since finding the brakes is too inconvenient.

One of the most draining parts of the pandemic for me has been the slow grinding loss of those small things.Losing the big things hurts, yes, but I find the small ones catch me off guard, and so they can hurt all the more for the lack of preparation.
My birthday is Monday, and tbh I'm finding myself increasingly sad that I can't celebrate w friends.It seems a small thing to be sad about, but life is made of those small things.

We said we wanted to find all SNPS between these 20 genomes - how do we evaluate? We do all pairwise alignments of the 20 truth genomes, and find SNPs between them. Then we needed to notice if a SNP between genomes 1,2 was the same as another SNP between genomes 3,4.   18/n

A pair with a similar situation to blue vs. purple is green vs. orange. Instead, use a dark green like 0x33A02C against a light green like 0xB2DF8A.In general, using two shades of the same color is a safer bet then using two different colors.17/ https://t.co/5G4fl4TaHz

Another one I see sometimes is blue vs. purple. This one is hit or miss. Sometimes I can see two colors, but even then, I can't tell you which is which.An alternative approach is to use a dark blue like 0x1F78B4 and light blue like 0xA6CEE3.16/ https://t.co/W6fN7Zjumx

I already told you red vs. green is bad, but it's super common with microscopy data because red and green are good colors for fluorescent tags.I suggest replacing red with magenta and using a lighter shade of green. I don't have microscopy data, but here's a scatterplot.15/ https://t.co/JB96mIG9Di

We often think red as a bright, attention-drawing color, but some color blind folks have a hard time seeing red against black. This is also true for text -- red text in a presentation just looks black to me.Instead of red vs. black, use blue vs. black.14/ https://t.co/f83FeL6IGy

Last data modality: categorical data. Oftentimes, we want to put two categories on the same plot.I'll use the iris dataset and show scatter plots of the sepal width vs. sepal length. The setosas will be one color and the versicolors and virginicas will be a second color.13/

more beneficial blood transfusion appears to be! (in their analysis).None of this is new. They reference our paper on anaemia in severe malaria, which said "naive mediation analysis via a simple adjustment for transfusion status results in selection (‚Äòcollider‚Äô) bias" https://t.co/4VnzhFPZRa

blood is correlated with not dying quickly! (You don't give a transfusion to some who has died)Therefore time to death is a confounder. The study didn't record time to death, so they can't stratify for it.As predicted by this confounding bias, the sicker you are, the

Disguising or modifying the cell surface is a common strategy for pathogenic bacteria to avoid the immune system and in developing resistance to phage. We think a large part of the dissolved organic phosphorus in the ocean might form as a consequence of this defense strategy. https://t.co/kTZWpJV7Ee

Gene context in other genomes suggests that phosphonglycoproteins are a common cell surface modification in the ocean. We think that this is probably because they are a kind of phage attachment or grazer defense mechanism.

All of Prochlorococcus' phosphonates were in the high molecular weight protein fraction. We think this is because phosphonates are incorporated into sugar chains that are attached to anchor proteins embedded in the outer membrane.

In fact, effectively no marine phosphonate producing genomes have the genes required to break C-P bonds. So if you are a phosphonate producer in the ocean it is unclear how you could get your P back from phosphonates once it is locked away in these compounds. https://t.co/W3d1er8RDV
Prochlorococcus doesn't rapidly consume its phosphonate reservoir upon P starvation. Prochlorococcus phosphonate producers also do not appear to have the genes necessary to break C-P bonds.

Turns out that Prochlorococcus can make A LOT of phosphonates - in some cases devoting up to 50% of cellular P quotas towards phosphonate production. Why would Prochlorococcus put so much P into phosphonate? Could it be a luxury storage strategy? We don't think so. https://t.co/6Hshjwyevd

At the time we started this project there was only one surface ocean, oligotrophic, free-living marine bacterial strain with phosphonate biosynthesis genes in culture. It happened to be a Prochlorococcus strain from our culture collection!
We also found that phosphonate producers increased with increasing depth in metagenomes - peaking near the DCM and what has been termed the "genomic transition zone." https://t.co/6Ne3s170l8

Technical standards are quite dry, but the standards from @GA4GH really make a difference to the delivery of genomic medicine and to the research to develop genomic medicine further.

GA4GH's global secretariat is based out of 4 institutions (@OICR_news, @broadinstitute, @sangerinstitute and @emblebi) and works with diverse driver projects from across Asia, Europe, Africa and the Americas.

@GA4GH's goal is to be like @w3c but for genomics, enabling responsible global data sharing, in-line with nations ethical and legal scheme to both bring research schemes to healthcare and enable research to happen on healthcare genomics data.

@emblebi is part of the international treaty organisation @embl. As such we can hire from any country worldwide, with nice location, campus, colleagues in an international setting. English is @embl's working language, and over 100 nationalities are present across @embl.

This position is based @emblebi, which is physically just south of Cambridge UK. You would part of the global secretariat of @GA4GH, the world's standard setting organisation for technical genomic standards spanning healthcare to research.

Are you an experienced software engineer/architect that wants to make an impact on global health? Can navigate practical technical standards delivery? Have management experience? Want a new challenge? Come join @GA4GH as our first Chief Standards Officer. https://t.co/Zhuxyw36kM

Somehow surprisingly both PTBP1 and HNRNPK also interact with the sense-antisense regions and this interaction is also essential for the SINEUP function. Much work ahead needed to further understand the interactome with polysomes and the structural basis of RNA-RBP complexes.

We characterized the compartments interactions happen, with PTBP1 interacting with the SINEUP in the nucleus and in the cytoplasm and HNRNPK with the target RNA in the nucleus, all of them interact in the cytoplasm (see Fig 11 for a model).

The paper shows where sense-antisense (SINEUPs) RNAs physical co-localize in the cells and how deletion of antisense region disrupts co-localizaiton. Next, mass-spectrometry identifies the protein interactome: we identified the functional one by functional assays.

Kudos to Naoko Toki, who defended today her PhD (and will be looking for a postdoc abroad) on this extensive work. After answering to all reviewers we ended up in a paper with 11 figures, covering broadly from discovery to function towards the mechanism.

As followers will know, I know that tweeting about making operational improvements to TTI is easy - actually getting it to work is far harder.

The other debate is less for columnists or opinion writers but just as important - how much better can we make Test-Trace-Isolate? What are the easy wins operationally here? These are details, details and details but really important.

Another debate goes to some hard truths, present in frameworks but super-charged; for example we recognise that the death of someone in their 80s is different from their 60s or 40s (in the UK this is in the QALY framework for the NHS) but how do we use this differential?

This goes to the far broader differential between quite a bit of public sector jobs (many of which one can work from home, no furlough needed) compared to private sector (how should support and furlough work).

Other things are really complex and more live policy and politics. Working from home works fine for many jobs, but for a variety of the key jobs for the functioning lockdown economy it does not (delivery drivers to nurses).

Some of these things feel mundane and petty - should golf courses stay open given the fact that golf is famously a way to wreck a good walk between two people. If we let people walk, why not golf? ( I posit this as an example - I don't want to get into this debate!).

<< but in addition it feels like this is economic + political policy on steroids, made fast - what outcomes do we want to optimise for (or minimise against)- what is fair and equitable in this compressed decision space with such weird thing (please remove these things not others)

So - although this is not a nice place to be, the horizon is definitely better looking forward. And although the weather in England is always pretty foul I hope this lockdown is far sharper, shorter and easier than March (fingers crossed!)

Vaccines are best not thought of as a fairy tale ending to this pandemic, but they are potent tools when they work (how potent we wont know until the Phase III trials are in). Past the early vaccine results there is the Spring and less favourable weather for the virus.

The fifth big thing is that we have real confidence that there will many vaccine trials reporting end of this year / beginning of next, and if one or more is successful, this will likely change many aspects of the epidemic.

One "card in our favour" is that at lower incidence levels some aspects of TTI - in particular Trace - just work better (or should work better - it is super complex to operationalise this stuff). This means lower incidence gives us a chance to have less restrictions and control.

This deserves the Dickensian quote again: "Annual income twenty pounds, annual expenditure nineteen nineteen and six, result happiness. Annual income twenty pounds, annual expenditure twenty pounds ought and six, result misery". Much the same with growth vs shrinkage here.

The fourth big thing is that although the mixture of TTI and restrictions in October was not enough to prevent growth, it *did* slow growth alot from the R ~2.5 to 3 in March vs 1.5-1.2 in October. We're not that far away from reasonable control of the virus transmission.

Frustratingly our increased knowledge does mean we now have a fuzzy view of a nasty long term follow on disease ("Long COVID") which we still need to get into focus more as it will be important to understand.

The third thing is that worldwide clinical research - of which some of the best has happened in the UK in particular the excellent RECOVERY trial - means less people die who are infected. Both single big things (knowing which drugs work) and thousands of little things here.
Just knowing where and how doesn't mean we can change things, but it is a good thing. It allow us to forecast and model with confidence; it allows us to understand where to focus.

The second is that our situational awareness - how much of the virus transmitting, and where - and knowledge of the virus (incubation period, disease profile at least for acute disease) is in a completely different space - we really know stuff.

The first, and most practical, is that hospitals will stay open for non-COVID procedures if at all possible + schools being open is the next highest priority (that's what I infer). Both of these are clearly about minimising the health and life impact aspects of more restrictions.

I spent a chunk of my graduate thesis work doing data visualization, data smoothing, and the like. I still sometimes cringe at the far-from-best-practices built into some tools I use at work, even though the theoretical numerical error introduced is insignificant.
There are reasons to prefer a Gaussian kernal smoothing algorithm as well, vs the rolling-window approach.  That upgrade takes -much- more work to get Excel to do right.

Sometimes I've forced Excel (or other spreadsheets) to place the rolling average profile where I think it should be, but it takes a bit more effort than I'd prefer.I know, I know. Like I said. It's my gripe.

Visually, we look at the figure and interpret the two profiles at the same horizontal distance as being the same time. The offset of the rolling average leads to that profile rising or falling after the raw data, leading to mental processing to correct for what you see.
